'''Jonathan Stevens Jackson''' (born May 11, 1982) is an American actor, musician, and author. He is best known for his role as [[Lucky Spencer]] in the television soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]'' (1993–1999, 2009–2011, 2015), which won him five [[Daytime Emmy Awards]]. He is also known for his roles in the films ''[[The Deep End of the Ocean (film)|The Deep End of the Ocean]]'' (1999), ''[[Tuck Everlasting (2002 film)|Tuck Everlasting]]'' (2002), ''[[Dirty Dancing: Havana Nights]]'' (2004), and ''[[Riding the Bullet (film)|Riding the Bullet]]'' (2004), as well as the television series ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]'' (2012–2018), for which he received a [[Critics' Choice Television Awards|Critics' Choice Television Award]] nomination.

==Early life==
Jackson was born in [[Orlando, Florida]], the son of Jeanine (née Sharp), an amateur [[ventriloquism|ventriloquist]] and businesswoman,<ref name="Columbian 10">{{cite web|last=Albright|first=Mary Ann|title=A hometown for 'General Hospital,' 'One Tree Hill' stars, musicians|url=http://www.columbian.com/news/2010/apr/19/online-bg-celebs/|work=The Columbian|publisher=columbian.com|access-date=January 19, 2013|date=April 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://norfolkdailynews.com/news/fundraiser-includes-actor-s-memorabilia/article_92f23ae4-2430-11e2-bcd0-0019bb30f31a.html?mode=jqm Fundraiser includes actor's memorabilia – News]. Norfolk Daily News (November 1, 2012). Retrieved on 2016-04-27.</ref> and Dr. Rick "Ricky Lee" Jackson, a [[family physician]],<ref name="CT Post" /> country musician and [[United States Congress|Congressional]] candidate in the state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]].<ref name="Columbian 12">{{cite web|last=Albright|first=Mary Ann|title=B.G. actor-musician goes country|url=http://www.columbian.com/news/2012/oct/06/jonathan-jackson-bg-actor-musician/|work=The Columbian|publisher=columbian.com|access-date=January 19, 2013|date=October 6, 2012}}</ref><ref name=nai>{{Cite news|last=Jewett|first=Dave|title=Article: Jackson Scores A Role In Major Film|publisher=The Columbian|date=October 6, 1997|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-4948001.html|access-date=September 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104214029/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-4948001.html|archive-date=November 4, 2012}}</ref> Jackson was raised in [[Battle Ground, Washington]], with his brother [[Richard Lee Jackson]], now an actor and musician, and his sister [[Candice Jackson]], now a lawyer, an author, and an official in the Trump administration.<ref name="Columbian 12" /> Jonathan attended Meadow Glade Elementary School.<ref name="Columbian 10" />

In 1991, Jackson's family took a trip to [[Universal Studios Hollywood]], where both Richard and Jonathan decided to pursue acting.<ref name="Columbian 10" /> The brothers took acting lessons in nearby [[Portland, Oregon]],<ref name="CT Post" /> before moving part-time to [[Burbank, California]] with their mother in 1993.<ref name="Columbian 10" />After doing various commercials, within six months<ref name="CT Post" /> Jackson won a role on the [[ABC Daytime]] [[soap opera]] ''[[General Hospital]]''. Jackson continued his studies as he worked, graduating high school at age 16.<ref name="Deep End" />

==Career==

===Acting===
Jackson's first notable role was [[Lucky Spencer]] on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]'', a role he first played from 1993 to 1999. Jackson won numerous awards for his work as Lucky. He was nominated for the [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Younger Actor in a Drama Series]] six times, winning first in 1995,<ref name="Emmys 95">{{cite news|title=Winners of Daytime Emmy Awards at a glance|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AN5EAAAAIBAJ&dq=jonathan-jackson&pg=4323%2C3243144|access-date=January 3, 2013|newspaper=Daily Union|date=May 21, 1995|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and again in 1998 and 1999,<ref name="2011 Emmys">{{cite web|last=Cormier|first=Matthew|title=Daytime Emmys Spotlight: Jonathan Jackson likely to be 'Lucky' again|url=http://www.goldderby.com/television/news/1175/daytime-emmys-spotlight-jonathan-jackson-likely-to-be-%27lucky%27-again.html|work=Gold Derby|publisher=goldderby.com|access-date=October 7, 2012|date=February 20, 2011}}</ref> making him the record holder for both nominations and wins for the Younger Actor category. He also won [[Soap Opera Digest Awards]] in 1995<ref name="SOD Awards 95">{{cite news|title='Days' big hit of soap awards night|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BZZQAAAAIBAJ&dq=soap%20opera%20digest%20awards%20jonathan%20jackson&pg=4505%2C4766636|access-date=January 21, 2013|newspaper=The Milwaukee Sentinel|date=February 18, 1995}}</ref> and 1999.<ref name="SOD Awards 99">{{cite news|title=ABC daytime dramas sweep Soap Opera Digest Awards|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=h4YNAAAAIBAJ&dq=15th%20soap%20opera%20digest%20awards&pg=6694%2C177090|access-date=January 21, 2013|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 1, 1999|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He was nominated for [[Young Artist Award]]s in 1996,<ref name="Young Artist Awards 96">{{cite web |url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms17.htm |title=17th Youth In Film Awards |access-date=February 2, 2013 |publisher=youngartistawards.org |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317154819/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms17.htm |archive-date=March 17, 2011 }}</ref> 1997<ref name="Young Artist Awards 97">{{cite web |url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms18.htm |title=18th Youth In Film Awards |access-date=February 2, 2013 |publisher=youngartistawards.org |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402060451/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms18.htm |archive-date=April 2, 2011 }}</ref> and 1999.<ref name="Young Artist Awards 99">{{cite web|url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms20.htm |title=20th Youth In Film Awards |access-date=February 2, 2013 |publisher=youngartistawards.org |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130907122639/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms20.htm |archive-date=September 7, 2013 }}</ref> He won ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'''s [[YoungStar Award]] in 1995,<ref name="Jackson McCullough 95">{{cite news|title=Awards|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SpwyAAAAIBAJ&pg=4786%2C4859771|access-date=February 3, 2013|newspaper=Lawrence Journal-World|date=October 28, 1995}}</ref> 1997,<ref name="Winners 1997">{{cite web|last=Ellis|first=Rick|title=1997's 2nd Annual Young Star Awards|url=http://www.allyourtv.com/awards/awardsyoungstar2nd.html|work=AllYourEntertainment, Inc.|publisher=www.allyourtv.com|access-date=February 2, 2013|date=May 4, 1997|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801031733/http://www.allyourtv.com/awards/awardsyoungstar2nd.html|archive-date=August 1, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> 1998 and 1999<ref name="1999 Winners">{{cite web|title=Rachel Leigh Cook, Britney Spears, Jonathan Jackson, Haley Joel Osment, Leelee Sobieski Among Winners at The Hollywood Reporter's 4th Annual YoungStar Awards|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Rachel+Leigh+Cook%2c+Britney+Spears%2c+Jonathan+Jackson%2c+Haley+Joel...-a057401156|work=Gale Group|publisher=Business Wire|access-date=February 2, 2013|date=November 8, 1999|archive-date=March 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316173043/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Rachel%20Leigh%20Cook%2C%20Britney%20Spears%2C%20Jonathan%20Jackson%2C%20Haley%20Joel...-a057401156|url-status=dead}}</ref> and was nominated in 2000. Jackson also became a popular "teen heartthrob" among fans,<ref name="EW May 99">{{cite magazine|last=Bonin|first=Liane|title=Lucky's Break|url=https://ew.com/article/1999/05/06/jonathan-jackson-will-leave-general-hospital/|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=January 21, 2013|date=May 6, 1999|archive-date=June 23, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623111710/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,84358,00.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="DD Jul 99">{{cite journal|title=The Lucky Star |journal=Daytime Digest|last=LiCausi|first=Debra|date=July 1999}}</ref> featured on [[fan magazine]]s<ref name="CT April 00">{{cite news|last=Cutler|first=Jacqueline|title=Jackson rising into a 'Purple Haze'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NvRLAAAAIBAJ&dq=jonathan-jackson%20prisoner-of-zenda&pg=3253%2C3121166|access-date=February 3, 2013|newspaper=Calhoun Times|date=April 15, 2000}}</ref> such as ''[[Tiger Beat]]'' and garnering many [[fan club]]s<ref name="Deseret 99">{{cite web|last=Vice|first=Jeff|date=March 12, 1999|title=Teenager immerses himself in 'Deep End of the Ocean' role|url=https://www.deseret.com/1999/3/12/19434075/teenager-immerses-himself-in-deep-end-of-the-ocean-role|access-date=February 9, 2013|work=Deseret News}}</ref> and internet [[fansite]]s.<ref name="Deep End" /> In 1999, he was named one of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine's 50 most beautiful people.<ref name="EW May 99" />

While working at ''General Hospital'', Jackson starred in his first feature film ''[[Camp Nowhere]]'', as Morris "Mud" Himmel in 1994.<ref name="Camp Nowhere">{{cite news|last=Sumner|first=Jane|title=Disney film 'Camp Nowhere'... a fun type of summer movie|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8CQgAAAAIBAJ&dq=jonathan-jackson%20camp-nowhere&pg=2120%2C5794229|access-date=January 20, 2013|newspaper=Sun Journal|date=August 27, 1994}}</ref> Also during this time he starred in [[made-for-television]] films ''[[Prisoner of Zenda, Inc.]]''<ref name="Tribune 2000">{{cite news|last=Cutler|first=Jacqueline|title=Jackson rising into a 'Purple Haze'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VmoxAAAAIBAJ&dq=jonathan-jackson%20prisoner-of-zenda&pg=2650%2C5997283|access-date=January 20, 2013|newspaper=Rome News-Tribune|date=April 14, 2000}}</ref> and ''The Legend of the Ruby Silver'',<ref name="Ruby Silver">{{cite news|title=Soap star making movie|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-6ssAAAAIBAJ&dq=jonathan-jackson%20ruby-silver&pg=6826%2C533583|access-date=January 20, 2013|newspaper=Star-News|date=January 3, 1996}}</ref> and made a guest appearance during [[List of Boy Meets World episodes#Season 5 (1997–1998)|Season 5]] of the ABC [[sitcom]] ''[[Boy Meets World]]''. In 1999, Jackson filmed ''[[The Deep End of the Ocean (film)|The Deep End of the Ocean]]'' shortly before leaving ''General Hospital,'' starring opposite [[Michelle Pfeiffer]].<ref name="Deep End">{{cite news |last1=King |first1=Susan |title='General Hospital' star jumps into 'Deep End'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AIMyAAAAIBAJ&dq=jonathan%20jackson%20general%20hospital&pg=5586%2C3394802|access-date=January 3, 2013|newspaper=Lawrence Journal-World|date=April 8, 1999|author2=The Los Angeles Times}}</ref> ''Deep End'' director [[Ulu Grosbard]] spoke of Jackson as "an enormously gifted actor. He brought a weight and a presence and chemistry with Michelle from the beginning. He's only 15 years old and he is a very serious actor who has both concentration and humor."<ref name="Deep End Quotes">{{cite news|title=Teen actors play Michelle Pfeiffer's sons|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UpQVAAAAIBAJ&pg=5478%2C2964090|access-date=January 21, 2013|newspaper=Manila Standard|date=June 25, 1999}}</ref> Pfeiffer added, "When Jonathan and I read together, it was like he was my own son. And we just went at each other in only this way that a mother and son could do. His reading was exhilarating."<ref name="Deep End Quotes" /> Jackson was nominated for YoungStar Awards in 1997 for ''Prisoner of Zenda, Inc.'' and 1999 for ''The Deep End of the Ocean''.<ref name="Awards 1999">{{cite web|last=Ellis|first=Rick|title=4th Annual YoungStar Award Nominations|url=http://www.allyourtv.com/awards/awardsyoungstar4th.html|work=AllYourEntertainment, Inc.|publisher=www.allyourtv.com|access-date=February 2, 2013|date=September 3, 1999|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801031738/http://www.allyourtv.com/awards/awardsyoungstar4th.html|archive-date=August 1, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

In December 1999, ''[[Newsweek]]'' magazine reported Jackson was likely to be taking on the role of [[Anakin Skywalker]] in ''[[Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones]]''. However, he was soon dropped from the running, and publications speculated the prior publicity had hurt his chances due to creator [[George Lucas]]' preference for privacy.<ref name=Skywalker>{{cite magazine|last=Johnson|first=Tricia|title=Star Search|url=https://ew.com/article/2000/02/25/next-anakin-skywalker/|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=January 21, 2013|date=February 25, 2000|archive-date=February 1, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201221827/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,275515,00.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Jackson continued his film career in 2000 with the independent film ''True Rights''<ref name="True Rights">{{cite web|last=Bates|first=James|title='Mockumentary' Takes Shot at Greedy Sellers of Tales |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-dec-24-fi-47061-story.html|work=The Los Angeles Times |access-date=January 20, 2013|date=December 24, 1999}}</ref> and the ABC television movie ''[[Trapped in a Purple Haze]]''.<ref name="Tribune 2000" /> Jackson also wrote and directed a short film with his brother Richard entitled ''Crystal Clear'', which won Best Dramatic Short Film and the Coen Brothers Award for Duo-Filmmaking at the [[Brooklyn Film Festival]].<ref name="Crystal Clear Awards">{{cite journal |url=http://www.geocities.ws/lovinrichnjj/wowfilmfestival.html |title=Jackson Brothers Wow Film Festival|journal=Soaps in Depth|date=October 17, 2000 |access-date=February 18, 2014}}</ref> In 2002, Jackson played one of his most well-known film roles as Jesse Tuck in ''[[Tuck Everlasting (2002 film)|Tuck Everlasting]]'', which he filmed simultaneously with ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]''. In 2004, Jackson filmed ''[[Dirty Dancing: Havana Nights]]'', and ''[[Riding the Bullet (film)|Riding the Bullet]]''. From 2008 through 2009, he had a recurring role as [[Kyle Reese#Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles|Kyle Reese]] in the hit Fox TV show ''[[Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles]]'', playing the father of [[John Connor#Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles|John Connor]] before the show was cancelled.

On September 29, 2009, it was announced that Jackson would return to ''General Hospital'' on October 27 to reprise the role of Lucky Spencer.<ref name=Soapnet>{{cite web|title=Jonathan Jackson to Return to Port Charles |url=http://sn.soapnet.go.com/news/article/jonathan-jackson-to-return-to-port-charles |work=SOAPnet |publisher=soapnet.com |access-date=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203015010/http://sn.soapnet.go.com/news/article/jonathan-jackson-to-return-to-port-charles |archive-date=February 3, 2013 }}</ref> In 2011, Jackson won his fourth Daytime Emmy and first [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor Award]].<ref name="2012 Emmys">{{cite web|title=Daytime Emmys 2012|url=http://tvline.com/2012/06/23/daytime-emmys-2012/|work=TV Line|publisher=tvline.com|access-date=October 7, 2012|date=June 23, 2012}}</ref> On November 7, 2011, it was announced that Jackson had decided to leave ''General Hospital''<ref name="Exit SOD">{{cite web|url=http://www.soapoperadigest.com/content/ghs-jonathan-jackson-out |title=GH's Jonathan Jackson Out! |publisher=Soap Opera Digest |date=November 7, 2011 |access-date=March 15, 2012}}</ref> and his final airdate was on December 23, 2011. His character is not planned to be recast or [[killed off]], leaving the door open for Jackson to return with the show in the future.<ref name="Jackson Quit Interview">{{cite web|last=Logan|first=Michael|title=Exclusive: Jonathan Jackson Discusses His Shocking Exit From General Hospital|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Jonathan-Jackson-Exit-1039760.aspx|work=TV Guide|publisher=tvguide.com|access-date=October 7, 2012|date=November 16, 2011}}</ref> In 2012, Jackson won his fifth Daytime Emmy and second consecutive win for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series.<ref name="2012 Emmys" /><ref name="TV Guide Emmy">{{cite web|last=Stanhope|first=Kate|title=General Hospital, Today Top Daytime Emmys|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Daytime-Emmy-Winners-1049168.aspx|work=TV Guide|publisher=tvguide.com|access-date=September 8, 2012|date=June 24, 2012}}</ref> On June 25, 2024, it was announced Jackson would return to ''General Hospital'' in the summer for a long run.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://deadline.com/2024/06/general-hospital-jonathan-jackson-returning-lucky-spencer-1235982759/ | title='General Hospital' is Bringing Back Jonathan Jackson as Lucky Spencer | date=June 25, 2024 }}</ref>

In 2012, he got the role of singer-songwriter [[Nashville (2012 TV series)#Main cast|Avery Barkley]] in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] drama ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]''.<ref name="Nashville Casting">{{cite web |last=Masters |first=Megan |date=February 23, 2012 |title=Pilot Scoop: GH's Jonathan Jackson Heads to Nashville, Mena Suvari Joins NBC Comedy |url=http://tvline.com/2012/02/23/jonathan-jackson-nashville-mena-suvari-nbc-comedy/ |access-date=January 19, 2013 |work=TV Line}}</ref> Along with the rest of the cast, Jackson sang and played the guitar himself on the series.<ref name="Columbian 12" />

===Music===
[[File:Jonathan Jackson - Enation.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Jackson performing with Enation in 2013]]
As a child, Jackson took guitar lessons and taught himself to play the piano.<ref name="CT Post" /> Growing up he had an evolving band with various family members. In 2000, the band included his brother, uncle and father and was named "Scarlet Road".<ref name="Tribune 2000" /> By 2002, Jackson and his brother Richard had named their group "Jono and the Rock".<ref name="CST 2002">{{cite news |url=http://www.jaehakim.com/entertainment-reviews/film-reviews/jonathan-jackson-from-general-hospital-to-everlasting-success/ |last=Kim|first=Jae-Ha|title=Jonathan Jackson: From 'General Hospital' to 'Everlasting' success |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|date=October 6, 2002 |access-date=February 18, 2014}}</ref>

The ensemble morphed into [[Enation (band)|Enation]], where Jackson is the [[frontman]], playing guitar, vocals and writing most of the songs.<ref name="CT Post">{{cite web|last=Christopher|first=Donna|title='General Hospital' star Jonathan Jackson's band to rock Marisa's|url=http://www.ctpost.com/music/article/General-Hospital-star-Jonathan-Jackson-s-band-3347664.php|work=Hearst Communications|publisher=ctpost.com|access-date=January 20, 2013|date=February 21, 2012}}</ref> Other band members include Jackson's brother Richard (drums), and their friend Jonathan Thatcher (bass, previously of [[Delirious?]])<ref name="Columbian 10" />

The band has released several albums and their song "[[Feel This (song)|Feel This]]" became a Top 10 hit on the [[iTunes]] national Rock Charts after it was featured on the [[The CW Television Network|CW]] television drama series ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]''.<ref name="Columbian 10" /> Enation's songs have also been featured on ''[[Riding the Bullet (film)|Riding the Bullet]]'',<ref name="CT Post" /> and ''General Hospital''.<ref name="GH song">{{cite web|title=Jackson's Song To Play On GH Today!|url=https://www.soapsindepth.com/posts/abc/jackson-s-song-to-play-on-gh-today-83586|work= Soaps in Depth|access-date=November 20, 2021|date=November 16, 2010}}</ref>

As well as performing as singer, guitarist & piano Jackson also wrote the song "The Morning of the Rain" featured on episodes 7 and 19 of the first season of ''Nashville''. Enation also landed on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top 10 (''Live From Nashville'' DVD, #9) and have garnered numerous radio and TV appearances including live performances on ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' and [[VH1]]'s ''Big Morning Buzz Live''.

In June 2020, Jackson recorded a song dedicated to the [[Hilandar]] and [[List of Serbian Orthodox monasteries|Serbian Orthodox monasteries]] in [[Kosovo]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Američki glumac napisao pesmu i snimio spot o manastirima na Kosovu |trans-title=An American actor wrote a song and recorded a video about monasteries in Kosovo |language=Bosnian |url=http://rs.n1info.com/Showbiz/a614832/Americki-glumac-napisao-pesmu-i-snimio-spot-o-manastirima-na-Kosovu.html |work=[[N1 (TV channel)|N1]] |access-date=June 29, 2020 |date=June 29, 2020 |archive-date=July 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200702104900/http://rs.n1info.com/Showbiz/a614832/Americki-glumac-napisao-pesmu-i-snimio-spot-o-manastirima-na-Kosovu.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Books===
In the spring of 2012, Jackson released a book of poetry under the name J. S. Jackson,<ref name="Pen name">{{cite web|title=Jackson Is A Published Poet!|url=https://www.soapsindepth.com/posts/abc/jackson-is-a-published-poet-84213|work=ABC Soaps in Depth|access-date=November 20, 2021|date=April 9, 2012}}</ref> titled ''Book of Solace and Madness.''<ref name="Columbian 12" /> In June 2012, he discussed his yet-to-be-released book entitled ''Acting in the Spirit,'' which would discuss the connection between his [[Eastern Orthodox Christian]] faith and his acting career.<ref name=Pravmir>{{cite web|title=Actor Jonathan Jackson Talks About His Journey to Orthodox Christianity|url=http://www.pravmir.com/actor-jonathan-jackson-talks-about-his-journey-into-orthodox-christianity-video-audio/|publisher=Pravmir.com|access-date=January 19, 2013|date=June 27, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121227123456/http://www.pravmir.com/actor-jonathan-jackson-talks-about-his-journey-into-orthodox-christianity-video-audio/|archive-date=December 27, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In November 2014, Jackson released ''The Mystery of Art: Becoming an Artist in the Image of God''.<ref>[http://store.ancientfaith.com/the-mystery-of-art/ The Mystery of Art – Ancient Faith Store]. Store.ancientfaith.com. Retrieved on April 27, 2016.</ref>

==Personal life==

===Family===
At age 20, Jackson married former ''[[General Hospital]]'' actress [[Lisa Vultaggio]] on June 21, 2002. Jackson told the ''Chicago Sun-Times'', "Some people thought we were a little young to get married. But we didn't see the need to wait. When it's right, it's right."<ref name="CST 2002" /> The couple moved to Jackson's hometown of Battle Ground, Washington, to raise their family.<ref name="Columbian 10" /> They have three children: Caleb (b. June 21, 2003), Adora (b. 2005), and Titus Gabriel (b. October 7, 2010).<ref name=Titus>{{cite web|title=Jackson's New Addition!|url= https://www.soapsindepth.com/posts/abc/jackson-s-new-addition-83541|work=Soaps in Depth|access-date=November 20, 2021|date=October 11, 2010}}</ref>

===Religion===
{{quote box
|width = 25em
|border = 1px
|align= right
|bgcolor= #F2F3F4
|fontsize = 88%
|quote = I've never presented Jesus in a car salesman sort of way. I don't believe in that for me. I don't want to turn anyone away because they're feeling pressured. The most positive influence I've had is people seeing the kind of life I'm living and the way I treat people. If people ask where that comes from, I'll say it comes from Jesus. And I'm definitely not ashamed of that.
|salign = right
|source = — Jackson on his faith, in 1998<ref name="SOD Aug 98" />}}

The son of [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]] parents,<ref name="Pravmir" /> Jackson was raised as a [[non-denominational Christian]]<ref name=Patheos>{{cite web|last=Rossi|first=Tony|title=Hollywood, Jesus and the Monks of Mount Athos: A Conversation with Actor Jonathan Jackson|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/christophers/2012/10/hollywood-jesus-and-the-monks-of-mount-athos-a-conversation-with-actor-jonathan-jackson/|work=Patheos|publisher=patheos.com|access-date=January 21, 2013|date=October 2, 2012}}</ref> and has always been vocal about his faith.<ref name="SOD 97">{{cite journal|title=Lucky's Charms|journal=[[Soap Opera Digest]]|date=September 1997<!--|access-date=January 20, 2013-->}}</ref> As part of his belief system, as a teen Jackson chose not to drink or do drugs.<ref name="Tribune 2000" /> Jackson was also a proponent of [[abstinence]] from [[premarital sex]].<ref name="CST 2002" /><ref name="SOD Aug 98">{{cite journal|title=The God Squad|journal=[[Soap Opera Digest]]|date=August 25, 1998<!--|access-date=January 21, 2013-->}}</ref> Jackson also often thanked [[God in Christianity|God]] during his award acceptance speeches.<ref name="SOD Aug 98" /> While Jackson was working on ''General Hospital'', he and his family held a [[home church]] in Burbank which various cast members attended, including Jackson's future wife Lisa Vultaggio.<ref name="Pravmir" /> Jackson explained how his beliefs affected his choice of acting roles in an interview with ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' in 1999, "I won't get involved with a movie that's a direct slap in the face of God. [...] I'm an actor, so I have to play people who believe differently than me. I would be willing to play a character that was completely unbelieving and anti-God, just as long as that wasn't the message of the whole movie."<ref name="EW May 99" />

In 2002, Jackson participated in the [[DKNY]]-sponsored "What's Your Anti-Drug?" campaign, posing for the 2003 calendar featured in ''[[Cosmogirl]]'' magazine,<ref name="DKNY campaign">{{cite web|title=DKNY Jeans and Youth Anti-Drug Campaign partner for celebrity calendar|url=http://www.iberkshires.com/story/8383/DKNY-Jeans-and-Youth-Anti-Drug-Campaign-partner-for-celebrity-calendar.html|work=Boxcar Media|publisher=iberkshires.com|access-date=January 21, 2013|date=November 11, 2002}}</ref> stating that his anti-drug was faith.<ref name=Brandweek>{{cite journal |author=Adweek |journal=Brandweek |year=2002 |volume=43 |issue=36–46|title=Brandweek|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zK8iAQAAMAAJ&q=%22what's+your+anti-drug%22+jonathan+jackson}}</ref> In 2012, Jackson and his family were baptized into the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://roadsfromemmaus.org/2012/02/27/from-general-hospital-to-the-hospital-of-souls-interview-with-jonathan-jackson/ |title=From General Hospital to the Hospital of Souls: Interview with Jonathan Jackson|date=February 28, 2012 |access-date=June 26, 2012}}</ref> Jackson cited a trip to [[Romania]] and [[Rome]] that first brought his attention to learning about the [[history of Christianity]].<ref name="Pravmir" /><ref name=Patheos /><ref name="Serbian">{{cite web|title=Jonatan Jackson – How I became Orthodox Christian| website=[[YouTube]] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-OEove_rlAM&t=168|access-date=January 24, 2016}}{{cbignore}}{{Dead Youtube links|date=February 2022}}</ref> In his acceptance speech for his 2012 [[Daytime Emmy Award]], he thanked the [[Holy Trinity]] as well as the monks on Orthodox monastic enclave [[Mount Athos]]. Jackson later explained in an interview, "These people [are] dedicating their lives to prayer, and not just praying for themselves, but truly praying for all of us. And then the thought kind of crossed my mind: with all the destruction, chaos and insanity that goes on in this world, if their prayers weren't happening, what would this world be like? I felt, personally, like I just wanted to thank them because I really believe that their prayers mean a lot."<ref name=Patheos />

As of September 18, 2020, ''OrthoChristian.com'' reports that Jackson had moved to Ireland to help support a new monastery being founded by the [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]] Metropolis of Southern and Western Europe. He explains in the interview, "It’s the main reason I moved, I have been praying for years for an Orthodox monastery to be founded in Ireland."<ref>{{Cite web|title=Actor-musician Jonathan Jackson moves to Ireland to help support burgeoning Romanian Orthodox monastery (+VIDEOS)|url=https://orthochristian.com/134069.html|access-date=2020-09-18|website=OrthoChristian.Com}}</ref>

